{"title_page": "Ryan Graves", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Ryan Graves (ice hockey)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ryan Graves\n| image              = Ryangraves-2018.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Graves in Ethiopia 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1983}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Diego]], California, US\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = Kauai, HI, US\n| nationality        = \n| known_for          = \n| education          = [[Miami University]]\n| employer           = \n| occupation         = Founder & CEO, Saltwater<br />SVP, [[Uber]] (December 2010-September 2017)<br />CEO, Uber (February\u2013December 2010)\n| title              = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = US$1.6 billion (March 2019)<ref name=\"Forbes profile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/ryan-graves/ |title=Forbes profile: Ryan Graves |publisher=Forbes |date= 4 March 2019 |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| boards             = [[Charity: Water]]\n| spouse             = Married\n| children           = 3\n}}\n'''Ryan Graves''' (born 1983) is an American billionaire businessman. He is the founder and CEO of Saltwater, and previously was the CEO, then SVP of Global Operations at [[Uber]], where he was also a director until 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/05/24/ubers-first-employee-ryan-graves-resigns-from-board/|title=Uber's original CEO, Ryan Graves, to step down from operating role|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGraves was born in [[San Diego]], California.<ref name=\"forbesellenhuet\">Ellen Huet, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenhuet/2015/03/02/uber-billionaires-garrett-camp-ryan-graves/ Uber Cofounder Garrett Camp, First Hire Ryan Graves Join FORBES Billionaires List], ''Forbes'', March 2, 2015</ref> An avid surfer, he grew up competing for his high school surf team at [[Horizon Christian Academy]]. Graves graduated from [[Miami University]] in [[Oxford, Ohio]] with a degree in Economics.\n\n==Career==\nGraves served as Uber's CEO and General Manager from February 2010 to December 2010, when his CEO role was replaced by one of Uber's founders [[Travis Kalanick]]. After that he served as the SVP of Global Operations at [[Uber]] until August 10, 2017.  He was often referred to as 'No. 2' and is very close to Uber's former CEO Kalanick. He is on the board of directors of the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/10/ubers-first-employee-ryan-graves-to-step-down.html|title=Uber's original CEO, Ryan Graves, to step down from operating role|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Graves announced his firm Saltwater, an investment company, focused on majority acquisitions of technology businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@ryangraves/saltwater-capital-investing-through-the-partner-equity-model-524bc21213a9|title=Saltwater Capital, Investing through the partner equity model|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nGraves serves on the Board of [[Charity: Water]].\n\n==Personal life==\nGraves is married, with three children, and lives on the island of Kaua'i, Hawaii.<ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.forbes.com/profile/ryan-graves/?list=40under40 40 Under 40 List Ryan Graves]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Graves, Ryan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n\n\n{{US-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Ryan Graves (ice hockey)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ryan Graves\n| image              = Ryangraves-2018.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Graves in Ethiopia 2018\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1983}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Diego]], California, US\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = Kauai, HI, US\n| nationality        = \n| known_for          = \n| education          = [[Miami University]]\n| employer           = \n| occupation         = Founder & CEO, Saltwater<br />SVP, [[Uber]] (December 2010-September 2017)<br />CEO, Uber (February\u2013December 2010)\n| title              = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = US$1.6 billion (March 2019)<ref name=\"Forbes profile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/ryan-graves/ |title=Forbes profile: Ryan Graves |publisher=Forbes |date= 4 March 2019 |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| boards             = [[Charity: Water]]\n| spouse             = Married\n| children           = 3\n}}\n'''Ryan Graves''' (born 1983) is an American billionaire businessman. He is the founder and CEO of Saltwater, and was the CEO, then SVP of Global Operations at [[Uber]], where he was a director until 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/05/24/ubers-first-employee-ryan-graves-resigns-from-board/|title=Uber's original CEO, Ryan Graves, to step down from operating role|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGraves was born in [[San Diego]], California.<ref name=\"forbesellenhuet\">Ellen Huet, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenhuet/2015/03/02/uber-billionaires-garrett-camp-ryan-graves/ Uber Cofounder Garrett Camp, First Hire Ryan Graves Join FORBES Billionaires List], ''Forbes'', March 2, 2015</ref> An avid surfer, he grew up competing for his high school surf team at [[Horizon Christian Academy]]. Graves graduated from [[Miami University]] in [[Oxford, Ohio]] with a degree in Economics.\n\n==Career==\nGraves served as Uber's CEO and General Manager from February 2010 to December 2010, when his CEO role was replaced by one of Uber's founders [[Travis Kalanick]]. After that he served as the SVP of Global Operations at [[Uber]] until August 10, 2017.  He was often referred to as 'No. 2' and is very close to Uber's former CEO Kalanick. He is on the board of directors of the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/08/10/ubers-first-employee-ryan-graves-to-step-down.html|title=Uber's original CEO, Ryan Graves, to step down from operating role|accessdate=10 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Graves announced his firm Saltwater, an investment company, focused on majority acquisitions of technology businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@ryangraves/saltwater-capital-investing-through-the-partner-equity-model-524bc21213a9|title=Saltwater Capital, Investing through the partner equity model|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nGraves serves on the Board of [[Charity: Water]].\n\n==Personal life==\nGraves is married, with three children, and lives on the island of Kaua'i, Hawaii.<ref name=\"Forbes profile\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.forbes.com/profile/ryan-graves/?list=40under40 40 Under 40 List Ryan Graves]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Graves, Ryan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Miami University alumni]]\n\n\n{{US-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rgsandiego123", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryan_Graves"}
{"title_page": "Phoenix Games B.V.", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = Phoenix Games\n| logo                = \n| type                = \n| industry            = [[Video games]]\n| fate                = \n| predecessor         = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor           = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded             = 2002<br>2003 (UK subsidiary)\n| founder             = Paul Share\nSteve Share\nWillie Horden\n| defunct             = 3rd August 2010\n| hq_location_city    = [[Nuenen]]\n| hq_location_country = NL\n| area_served         = Europe\n| key_people          = Paul Share (CEO)\n| products            = Buget video games, movies\n| owner               = Paul Share, Steve Share\n| num_employees       = 10\n| num_employees_year  = 2003\n| parent              = [[Midas Interactive Entertainment]]\n| divisions           = Phoenix Games B.V.\nPhoenix Games LTD.\nPhoenix Games Asia\n| subsid              = \n| website             = {{URL|http://web.archive.org/web/20080821123206/http://www.phoenixgamesgroup.com|http://www.phoenixgamesgroup.com}}\n}}\n'''''Phoenix Games''''' is a partly-defunct Dutch video game publisher founded by Willie Horden, Paul Share and Steve Share, that released a large amount of low-effort titles for the Sony [[PlayStation]], [[PlayStation 2]], [[Nintendo DS]], [[Microsoft Windows]] and the Nintendo [[Wii]]. They had contracts with over 50 developer Studios around the globe.\n\nThey published games based on [[Dingo Pictures]] films on the aforementioned consoles (barring Windows). Their last known published game was Lion and the King 3 on Nintendo DS, released on February 12th, 2010.\nThe German Video Game Archive claims that they published 99 games on the PlayStation 2 alone.<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.gamereset.de/va/coverstrophen.html Coverstropfen] on German Videogamearchive</ref>\n\n== Phoenix Games Group ==\nPhoenix Games was devised between three companies, Phoenix Games B.V., Phoenix Games Ltd. and Phoenix Games Asia. The group was an exhibitor at E3 in 2005.<ref>[https://www.giantbomb.com/e3-2005/3015-3437/ E3 2005] Giantbomb.com</ref> Also they went to ECTS2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040829195327/http://phoenixgamesltd.com/ects.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2004-08-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Phoenix Games B.V. ===\nFounded in May 2002 by Willie Horden<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/williehorden/?originalSubdomain=nl Willie Horden] LinkedIn Profile - Only Visible for Logged in Users</ref> and Paul and Steve Share. They had a UK subsidiary based in Leicester. They were exhibitors of E3 2004<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2004-may-14-et-mcnamara14-story.html|title=Getting an education in video games at E3|date=2004-05-14|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> 2005<ref>[https://www.giantbomb.com/e3-2006/3015-3439/ List of Exhibitos at E3 2006] on Giantbomb.com</ref> and 2006<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.giantbomb.com/e3-2006/3015-3439/|title=E3 2006 (Concept)|website=Giant Bomb|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and were located in De Pinckart 46g, 5674 CC Nuenen in the Netherlands.\n\nPhoenix Games B.V. declared bankruptcy on August 3rd, 2010. On March 27th, 2012 the bankruptcy was suspended due to a lack of income.<ref>[https://drimble.nl/faillissementen/noord-brabant/eindhoven/17160750/phoenix-games-holland-bv.html Phoenix Games] on drimble.nl (Dutch)</ref>\n\n=== Phoenix Games LTD ===\nPhoenix Games LTD is still an active registered company in the UK located at 48 Boundary Rd, Newark, Notts, United Kingdom, NG24 4AL.<ref>[https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/08493645/officers Phoenix Games LTD.] at UK Goverment Companies House</ref> Their original address was 53 Malcolm Way, Snaresbrook, London, E11 1PW.\n\n=== Phoenix Games Asia ===\nPhoenix Games Asia was located at 24 Sukhumvit, Soi 11, Unit 3B, Sukhumvit Road Bangkok 10110, Thailand, Klongtoey Nua, Wattana. It is unknown if this company still exists or if it was closed down.\n\n==Games==\nThe company's titles took only around 3-5 months to develop. At some point, they planned releasing their games to the PSP<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news140704psp|title=75 reasons to buy PlayStation Portable|last=Bramwell|first=Tom|date=2004-07-14|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beta.gamesmarkt.de/details/182663|title=Spielspa\u00df zum Mitnahmepreis|website=beta.gamesmarkt.de|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and Xbox. The original store prices of the games were between 6.99 - 12.99 GBP. The mauals ans games are availeble in English, French, German, Italian, Portuguese and Spanish.\n\nIn Italy, the company DB-Line distributed the movies and games until 2007.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LHaJNKEmUcU Phoenix Games Group Web Advertisements (2003 - 2008)]\n</ref> In Spain, at least one game was distributed by [[Atari]].\n\nOn 4th November 2002 they announced their partnership with Japanese company [[Altron]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040830004253/http://phoenixgamesltd.com/altron.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2004-08-30|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and Italian developer NAPS<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040830004520/http://phoenixgamesltd.com/naps.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2004-08-30|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>. In Dezember 2002 they announced that they bought the rights to \"[[Dragon's Lair|Dragons Lair]]\", \"[[Space Ace]]\", \"[[Who Shot Johnny Rock?|Who shot Johnny Rock?]]\" and \"[[Mad Dog McCree]]\"from [[Digital Leisure]] in Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040830004450/http://phoenixgamesltd.com/arcade.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2004-08-30|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n<nowiki> </nowiki>In February 2003 they announced that their games will distributed by \"Just\" in the UK<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040830004433/http://phoenixgamesltd.com/just.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2004-08-30|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>,Joag in Italy, SGDiffusion in France and N-Tec in Hungary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040829195547/http://phoenixgamesltd.com/newpartners.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2004-08-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In the same year they announced their \"Super Buget Line\" for PS2 and Xbox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news150803budget|title=New PS2, Xbox super-budget ranges|last=International|first=GamesIndustry|date=2003-08-15|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 22nd August 2003 they announced that \"New Media Agency\" will translate and distribute their games in Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040829195621/http://phoenixgamesltd.com/newgerman.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2004-08-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> On 14th October 2003 they announced that Softwrap will be their Distributor in Europe<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040829195333/http://phoenixgamesltd.com/softwrap.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2004-08-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 it was reportet that 80 games would be released on PlayStation 1, 2 and PC that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beta.gamesmarkt.de/details/125210|title=Kellas \u00fcbernimmt Vertrieb von Phoenix Games|website=beta.gamesmarkt.de|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In 2004 40 titles were announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://beta.gamesmarkt.de/details/159745|title=Trend Verlag baut Budgetprogramm aus|website=beta.gamesmarkt.de|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 they went into a partnership with [[Data Design System|Data Design]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/news291104monsterarenas|title=Phoenix Games signs UK-devved truck racer|last=Bramwell|first=Tom|date=2004-11-29|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 they announced 12 games for the Nintendo DS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2008-02-28-phoenix-plans-twelve-games-to-avoid-this-year.html|title=Phoenix plans twelve games to avoid this year|website=Engadget|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn the first year they expected 4 to 5 million sold units worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031111142023/http://www.phoenixgamesgroup.com/company3.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2003-11-11|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2010 Phoenix Games re-released some of their Games rebranded as \"Simulations\" to German PC audiences.\n\nDo to the populatity of their games on the Internet and the sometimes small prints, some games are selling for a good amount of money.\n\n== Other ==\nAll 99 PS2 covers were featured on the 2013 Gamescom art gallery \"Coverstrophen\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2015 the [[Angry Video Game Nerd]] covered \"Snow White and the 7 Clever Boys in his \"Bad Game Cover Art\" Series.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UdfFiUM10FU</ref>\n\nPaul Share also founded [[Midas Interactive]] in 1998.\n\nThe PS2 boxart for Peter Pan stole official Kingdom Hearts artwork, more specifically, artwork depicting Destiny Islands, a world in the series.<ref>[https://www.reddit.com/r/KingdomHearts/comments/438v59/you_guys_know_those_terrible_phoenix_games_with/ Reddit Post]  by u/TheGamedawg</ref>\n\nBoth before and after the group existed, there were companies that were formed with the same name. From 1978 to 1981, an American company named [[Phoenix Games]] produced games, best known for the game [[Bushido (role-playing game)|Bushido]]. In 2019, Klaas Kersing founded a gaming company in Germany with the same name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutsche-startups.de/2019/04/05/klaas-kersting-phoenix-games/|title=Klaas Kersting gr\u00fcndet mit Phoenix Games eine Art Spiele-Investor|date=2019-04-05|website=deutsche-startups.de|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nThe Game Paccie is curretly lost.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lostmediawiki.com/Paccie_(lost_PlayStation_2_game;_existence_unconfirmed;_2004)|title=Paccie (lost PlayStation 2 game; existence unconfirmed; 2004) - The Lost Media Wiki|website=lostmediawiki.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==Known staff==\nIn total 10 people worked with Phoenix Games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030806023403/http://www.phoenixgamesgroup.com/company1.html|title=Phoenix Games: PS2, PSX, PC and XBOX|date=2003-08-06|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==== Phoenix Games B.V. (2002-2010) ====\n* Paul Share (CEO/President)\n* Willie (Will) Horden (sales director until February 2005/managing director until June 2009)\n\n* Steve Share (sales manager)\n\n* Ilse van de Vossenberg Vogels (production administrator)\n\n* Maarten van Schaik (development manager)\n\n==== Phoenix Games Ltd. ====\n* Mark Hustle (born: July 1963) - director since 2013.\n* Simon Hamer (European Sales Manager)\n* Ian Smith (UK Sales Manager)<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20030805211355/http://www.phoenixgamesgroup.com/contact.html</ref>\n==== Phoenix Games Asia ====\nNo official employees are known.\n\n== List of movies published ==\n\n=== Dingo Pictures movies ===\n*''...noch mehr Dalmatiner:'' released as ''Dalmatians 2,'' ''Dalmatians 3'' & ''Dalmatians 4'' (for the PS, PS2 and the Wii/DS, respectively)\n* ''Das unglaubliche Fussballspiel der Tiere:'' released as ''Animal Football'' & ''Animal Soccer World'' (for the PS and PS2, respectively)\n*''Atlantis: Der verlorene Kontinent:'' released as ''Atlantis: The Lost Continent ''& ''Empire of Atlantis ''(for the PS and PS2, respectively)\n*''Toys: Das Geburtstagsgeschenk:'' released as ''Toys ''&'' The Toys Room ''(for the PS and PS2, respectively)\n*''Abenteuer im Land der Dinosaurier:'' released as ''Dinosaurs ''&'' Dinosaur Adventure ''(for the PS and PS2, respectively)\n*''Ein Fall f\u00fcr die M\u00e4usepolizei:'' released as ''Detective Mouse'' & ''The Mouse Police ''(for the PS and PS2, respectively)\n*''Winkie der kleine B\u00e4r:'' released as ''Winky the Little Bear'' & ''Countryside Bears'' (for the PS and PS2, respectively)\n* Der K\u00f6nig der Tiere: das grosse Abenteuer: released as ''Lion and the King 2, Son of the Lion King'' & ''Lion and the King 3 ''(for the PS, PS2 and the Wii/DS, respectively)\n\n=== Other movies released ===\n* Peter Pan (Longsoft Multimedia): released as ''Peter Pan'' & ''Peter Pan's Playground'' (PS2, Wii, DS)\n* Snow White and the Magnificent Seven (Longsoft Multimedia): released as Snow White and the 7 Clever Boys &Princess Snow White (PS2)\n* Cinderella (Longsoft Multimedia): released as ''Cinderella'' & ''Cinderella's Fairytale'' (Wii, PS2)\n* Pinocchio (Longsoft Multimedia): released as ''Adventures of Pinocchio'' (Wii, PS2, DS)\n* Hansel & Gretel (Longsoft Multimedia): released as ''Hansel & Gretel ''(PS2)\n* Hercules (Pure Magic): released as ''Herkules'' & ''Legend of Herkules'' (PS, PS2)\n* Mulan (Django Studios): released as ''Legend of Mulan'' & ''Mighty Mulan ''(PS, PS2)\n\n== List of Games ==\n\n=== Sony PlayStation ===\n* January 2003: Cindy's Caribian Holiday\n*January 2003: Cindy's Fashion World\n*14. March 2003: All Star Watersports\n*14. March 2003: Trickshot 7 Games\n*28. March 2003: [[Football Madness]]\n*28. March 2003: Pro Backgammon\n*1. May 2003: Rox\n*27. June 2003: Hot Shot\n*27 June 2003: King Of Bowling 3\n*8 August [[2003 in video gaming|2003]]: [[Baldies]]\n*8. August 2003: Block Buster\n*15. November 2003: 5 Star Racing\n*2003: [[Ballerburg|Ballerburg: Castle Chaos]]\n*2003: Buttsubushi\n*2003: Destructo 2\n*2003: Flying Squadron\n*2003: [[Paradise Casino]]\n*2003: Superbike Masters\n*2003: All Star Action\n*2003: Checkmate 2\n*2003: Homerun\n*2. March 2004: Robin Hood: The Siege\n*9. August 2004: Space Rider\n*9. August 2004: Truck Rally\n*12. August 2004: [[Sonic Wings Special]]\n*19. August 2004: Omega Assault\n*15. November 2004: Jet Ace\n*2004: Rhythm Beat\n*2004: Silent Iron\n*2004: Wanted\n* 2005: SHOOT\n* 2003: Robopit 2\n\n=== Sony PlayStation 2 ===\n* 2003: Cool Shot\n*2003: Homerun\n*1. May 2004: Paccie\n*31. August 2004'': [[Kidz Sports Basketball]]''\n*8. October 2004: Xtreme Speed\n*22. October 2004: Furry Tales\n*5. November 2004: RC Toy Machines\n*19 November 2004: Arcade Action: 30 Games\n*2004: European Tennis Pro\n* 2004: Air Raid 3\n*2004: Road Rage 3\n*25. February 2005: Crazy Golf\n*4. March 2005: X-treme Quads\n*25. March 2005: Board Games Gallery\n*25. March 2005: Vegas Casino 2\n*25. March 2005: Monster Trux Extreme\n*24. June 2005: Shadow of Ganymede\n*15. July 2005: Doomsday Racers\n*15. July 2005: Hamster Heroes\n*30. September 2005: Urban Constructor\n*2005: Finkles World\n*2005: Girl Zone\n*2005: Habitrail Hamster Ball\n*2. January 2006: Saint & Sinner\n* 21. April 2006: Arcade USA\n*21. April 2006: Obliterate\n*28. June 2006: Puzzle Party: 10 Games\n*June 2006: Search & Destroy\n*28. July 2006: 21 Card Games\n*28. July 2006: City Soccer Challenge\n*28. July 2006: London Cap Challenge\n*28. July 2006: Maniac Mole\n*29. September 2006: Carwash Tycoon\n*29. September 2006: Chemist Tycoon\n*6. October 2006: Downhill Slalom\n*6. October 2006: [[G-Force (video game)|G-Force]]\n*6. October 2006: Robin Hood: The Siege 2\n*6. October 2006: Snow Rider\n*13. October 2006: Combar Ace\n*13. October 2006: D-Unit Drift Racing\n*27. October 2006: Clumsy Slumsy\n*27. October 2006: Drag Racer USA\n*3. November 2006: K.O. King\n*