an]]. Essays and studies in ''Dikan. Vol. 1'' ''(1969-1971)'', by [[Lazo Sredanovi\u0107]], [[Nikola Leki\u0107]] et al, \"Everest Media\", Belgrade 2013. {{ISBN|978-86-7756-027-0}} and ''Dikan. Vol. 2 (1972-1983)'', \u201eInformatika\u201c & \u201eEverest media\u201c, Beograd 2015. {{ISBN|978-86-84497-49-1}}\n* Stefanovi\u0107, Zoran. \"Siktaj bez zvuka: kriti\u010dka istorija serijala Kobra\", in: Kobra, Vol. 1, by Svetozar Obradovi\u0107 and [[Branislav Kerac]], \"Darkwood\", Belgrade, 2013, pp. 157\u2013189. {{ISBN|978-86-6163-139-9}}\n* Stojanovi\u0107, Marko et al. ''Leskova\u010dki strip 1950-2010'', own publication, Leskovac, Serbia, 2010.\n* [[\u017divojin Tamburi\u0107|Tamburi\u0107, \u017divojin]], Zdravko Zupan and Zoran Stefanovi\u0107, with foreword by [[Paul Gravett]]. ''[[The Comics We Loved|The Comics We Loved: Selection of 20th Century Comics and Creators from the Region of Former Yugoslavia'']], \"Omnibus\", Belgrade, Serbia, 2011. {{ISBN|978-86-87071-03-2}}\n* [[Bogdan Tirnani\u0107|Tirnani\u0107, Bogdan]]. ''Ogled o Paji Patku, ''\u201eXX vek\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1989.\n* [[Svetozar Tomi\u0107|Tomi\u0107, Svetozar]]. ''Strip, poreklo i zna\u010daj, ''\u201eForum\u201c, Novi Sad, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1985.\n* [[Anica Tucakov|Tucakov, Anica]]. ''Strip u Srbiji 1975-1995, ''Zadu\u017ebina \u201eAndrejevi\u0107\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 2000.\n* Various. ''Izme\u0111u igre i podviga: Ko je i kako stvarao De\u010dje novine'', ed. by Aleksandar Lazarevi\u0107, \u201eRavera Press\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1996.\n* Zupan, Zdravko, \u201eLes \u00e9ditions europ\u00e9ennes du journal de Mickey \u2013 Yougoslavie\u201c, ''Le collectionneur de Bandes Dessin\u00e9es'' 105, Paris, France, 2005.\n* Zupan, Zdravko, \u201eThe Golden Age of Serbian comics, Belgrade Comic Art 1935-1941\u201c'', International Journal of Comic Art, ''Drexel Hill, PA, USA, 2000.\n* Zupan, Zdravko. ''Vek stripa u Srbiji, ''Kulturni centar, Pan\u010devo, Serbia, 2007.\n* [[Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107 (writer)|\u017divkovi\u0107 Zoran]]. ''Enciklopedija nau\u010dne fantastike ''1-2, \u201eProsveta\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1990.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150323215621/http://www.rastko.org.rs/strip/zzupan-golden_age.html The Golden Age of Serbian Comics] {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://www.paulgravett.com/articles/article/comics_culture_in_yugoslavias_ Comics Culture in Yugoslavia by Paul Gravett] {{in lang|en}}\n*[http://www.rastko.org.rs/strip/zstefanovic-petlic_c.html Konstantin Kuznjecov, ''Fairytale about Tsar Saltan/The Tale of the Golden Cockerel'', 1940] {{in lang|sr}}\n*[http://www.stripvesti.com/ Strip vesti (comics news)] {{in lang|sr}}\n*[http://www.kosmoplovci.net/studiostrip/indexx.html Kosmoplovci (Serbian underground comics)] {{in lang|sr}}\n*[http://www.usus.org.rs/ The Association of Serbian comics artists/Udru\u017eenje stripskih umetnika Srbije] {{in lang|sr}}\n\n{{Comics}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox comics nationality\n|converted=y\n|date = Late 19th century\n|notable publishers =[[Politika]], [[De\u010dje novine]], [[Borba (newspaper)|Borba]], [[Forum (publisher)|Forum]], [[Dnevnik (Serbia)|Dnevnik]]\n|notable titles     =''[[Mika Mi\u0161]]'', ''[[Politikin Zabavnik]]'', ''[[Kekec (magazine)|Kekec]]'', ''[[Nikad robom]]'', ''[[YU strip]]'', ''[[Stripoteka]]''\n|notable people =[[\u0110or\u0111e Loba\u010dev]], [[Branislav Kerac]], [[Zoran Janjetov]]\n|notable series =\n|notable characters =[[Zigomar (comics)|Zigomar]], [[Dikan]], [[Mirko and Slavko]], [[Kobra (comic book)|Kobra]], [[Cat Claw]]\n|lang1      = [[Serbian language|Serbian]]\n|related1   = [[European comics]]\n}}\n'''Serbian comics''' are [[comics]] produced in [[Serbia]].\n\nComics are called ''stripovi'' in [[Serbian language|Serbian]] (singular ''strip'') and come in all shapes and sizes, merging influences from [[American comic book|American comics]] to [[Franco-Belgian comics|bandes dessin\u00e9es]].\n\nComics started developing in Serbia in the late 19th century, mostly in [[Humor magazine|humor]] and [[Children's literature|children\u2019s magazines]]. From the 1920s to the end of the 1980s, Serbian comics were part of the larger [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] comics scene; a large number of titles was published from 1932 to 1991, mainly in [[Serbo-Croatian language]]. After [[Yugoslav Wars|the breakup of Yugoslavia]] and the crisis in the 1990s, Serbian comics have experienced a revival.\n\n== History ==\n=== \"The Golden Age\" (1932-1941) ===\n{{Quote box |quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center|quote=When we started out, nobody thought how it\u2019d all turn out, or what it\u2019d become. How far we\u2019d come! Simply put, we liked the new medium, although nobody realized it was a new medium.|source=- [[\u0110or\u0111e Loba\u010dev]], 1985|align=left|width=33%}}\n\n[[File:Zigomarcomics.jpg|left|thumb|''[[Zigomar (comics)|Zigomar]]'', created by artist Nikola Navojev and writer Branko Vidi\u0107 and heavily influenced by foreign [[masked hero]] comics, is considered one of the most notable titles of the \"Golden Age of Serbian Comics\".]]\n\nIn 1932 ''Veseli \u010detvrtak'' (''Merry Thursday''), an illustrated magazine for children, appeared in [[Belgrade]]; an unusually large amount of space was allotted to [[cartoon]]s. The magazine featured foreign works such as ''[[The Katzenjammer Kids]]'' and ''[[Felix the Cat]]'', but also ''Do\u017eivljaji Mike Mi\u0161a'' (''The Adventures of Mika the Mouse''), a [[Mickey Mouse]] [[pastiche]] by Serbian authors. Other [[Weekly newspaper|weeklies]] and dailies such as ''Vreme'' and ''Pravda'' followed suit.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/kultura/vesti/tri-generacije-srpskih-strip-autora-u-francuskom-institutu-od-djorda-lobaceva-do/c0f9mfd|title=Tri generacije srpskih strip autora u Francuskom institutu, od \u0110or\u0111a Loba\u010deva do Alekse Gaji\u0107a|date=2015-11-27|language=sr-SP|access-date=2016-07-17}}</ref> In 1934, one whole page of ''[[Politika]]'' newspaper was devoted to ''[[Secret Agent X-9]]''. In addition to adventure comics, [[Walt Disney]]'s [[funny animal]]s were also popular at the time, especially Mickey Mouse, whose name would be used in the titles of a number of Yugoslav comic publications: ''Mika Mi\u0161'', ''Mikijeve novine'' (''Mickey's Newspapers''), ''Mikijevo carstvo'' (''Mickey's Empire''). An editor named Du\u0161an Timotijevi\u0107 named the new art form \"strip\", after English \"[[comic strip]]\".\n\nIn 1934, the first two specialized [[comic magazine]]s appeared - ''Strip'' and ''Crtani film'' (''Cartoon''). Their appearance and content were influenced by the Italian magazines ''[[Topolino]]'', ''[[L'Audace]]'' and ''[[L'Avventuroso]]'', as well as French magazines ''[[Le Journal de Mickey]]'' and ''[[Hop-l\u00e0!]]''. [[White \u00e9migr\u00e9|Russian immigrant]] [[Nikola Navojev]] debuted in the pages of ''Strip'' with his works. Although he died at the age of 27,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/n/navojev_nikola.htm|title=Nikola Navojev|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref> Navojev was a prolific author who created a number of characters for Strip, of which [[Jungle girl (stock character)|jungle girl]] Tarcaneta (''Tarzanette'') is best-known today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=475877|title=Srpska ''pin-up'' divljaku\u0161a|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref> In 1935, inspired by the adventures of [[Alex Raymond]]'s X-9, Vlastimir Belki\u0107 created the first original character in Serbian comics named Hari Vils.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/b/belkic_vlastimir.htm|title=Vlastimir Belkic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref> Similarly, other two Russian immigrants, artist [[\u0110or\u0111e Loba\u010dev]] and writer Vadim Kurganski, began working on their first comic, called ''Krvavo nasledstvo'' (''Bloody Heritage''), serialized in the illustrated periodical ''Panorama''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/l/lobacev_djordje.htm|title=Djordje Lobacev|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref> Not only was it the first successful modern comic produced in Serbia, but also the first title set in Yugoslavia.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tragom narodne ma\u0161te|last=Loba\u010dev|first=\u0110or\u0111e|publisher=De\u010dje novine|year=1989|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Gospodar smrti.jpg|right|thumb|''[[Master Death]]'', drawn by \u0110or\u0111e Loba\u010dev and published in ''Mikijevo carstvo'', is one of the most notable titles of the \"Golden Age of Serbian comics\". Published on the eve of World War II, ''Master Death'' carried a strong anti-war message.]]\n\nMost of the Golden Age artists were Russian immigrants, collectively known as the Belgrade Circle and gathered at first around the ''Mika Mi\u0161'' magazine. Soon enough it was transformed into a real comic magazine, reprinting foreign classics like ''[[Prince Valiant]]'', [[Phantom (comics)|''Phantom'']] and ''[[Flash Gordon]]'', but also publishing comics by the local authors. ''Mika Mi\u0161'' lasted from 1936 to 1941, when it ended with issue 505.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wolfstad.com/dcw/serbia-and-montenegro/mika-mis-1936-1941/|title=Mika Mis (1936 - 1941) by Aleksandar J. Ivkovic < Serbia and Montenegro @ Disney Comics Worldwide|website=www.wolfstad.com|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref> Its domination would not be questioned until 1939 and the emergence of ''Mikijevo carstvo'' and ''[[Politikin Zabavnik]]''. The key figures behind all three publications were editors Aleksandar J. Ivkovi\u0107 and Milutin Ignja\u010devi\u0107.<ref name=\":0\" /> From 1935 to 1941 about twenty comic magazines were launched in Serbia, published weekly and bi-weekly, mostly in black-and-white. They were sold throughout Yugoslavia. In order to boost sales in the western parts of Yugoslavia (today's [[Croatia]] and [[Slovenia]]), some publications were printed not only in the [[Serbian Cyrillic alphabet|Serbian Cyrillic]] but also [[Latin alphabet]]. Comics were distributed through [[convenience store]]s, [[Newsagent's shop|newsstands]] and [[Newspaper hawker|newsboys]], with an average print run of 10,000 - 30,000 copies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rastko.rs/strip/zzupan-golden_age.html|title=[Projekat Rastko] Zdravko Zupan: The Golden Age of Serbian Comics|website=www.rastko.rs|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref>\n\nThe notable works were inspired by cultural classics and [[Serbian folklore]]. The shortlist includes [[Ivan \u0160en\u0161in]]'s ''Hrabri vojnik \u0160vejk'' (an adaptation of [[Jaroslav Ha\u0161ek]]'s novel ''[[The Good Soldier \u0160vejk]]'') and ''Zvonar Bogorodi\u010dine crkve'' (and adaptation of [[Victor Hugo]]'s novel ''[[The Hunchback of Notre-Dame]]''), [[Sergej Solovjev]]'s ''Carev \u0161titono\u0161a'' (''Emperor's Squire''), ''Robin Hud'' (''[[Robin Hood]]'') and ''Ajvanho'' (an adaptation of [[Walter Scott]]'s ''[[Ivanhoe]]''), Loba\u010dev's ''[[Master Death]]'', ''Baron Minhauzen'' (an adaptation of [[Rudolf Erich Raspe]]'s ''[[Baron Munchausen|The Surprising Adventures of Baron Munchausen]]'') and ''Biber\u010de'' (''Pepper-Boy'', based on the Serbian folk [[fairytale]] of the same name), [[Konstantin Kuznjecov]]'s ''Grofica Margo'' (''Countess Margo'') and ''Bajka o caru Saltanu'' (an adaptation of [[Alexander Pushkin]]'s [[poem]] ''[[The Tale of Tsar Saltan]]''). Unlike most of his contemporaries, [[Sebastijan Lechner]] also wrote his own scripts, such as ''D\u017earto''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/l/lehner_sebastijan.htm|title=Sebastijan Lechner|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref> Similarly, Navojev teamed up with [[Script (comics)|comics writer]] [[Branko Vidi\u0107]] to create [[Zigomar (comics)|''Zigomar'']]. Some of the titles were reprinted in [[France|French]] and [[Turkey|Turkish]] magazines,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kayaozkaracalar.blogspot.com/2008/12/yugoslavian-comics-in-turkey-part-1.html|title=The MysterIous Flame of Queen Loana: YUGOSLAVIAN COMICS IN TURKEY - PART 1: COUNTESS MARGO|last=\u00d6zkaracalar|first=Kaya|date=2008-12-23|website=The MysterIous Flame of Queen Loana|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> while ''Zigomar'' was also published in [[Bulgaria]], [[Italy]] and [[Argentina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.phantomwiki.org/Zigomar_vs._The_Phantom#Reprints|title=Zigomar vs. The Phantom - PhantomWiki|website=www.phantomwiki.org|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref> \n\nOther creators of \"the first generation\" included Vsevold Guljevi\u010d, Aleksije Ranhner, \u0110or\u0111e Jankovi\u0107, Moma Markovi\u0107, Marijan Ebner, Vojin \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107, Nikola Ti\u0161\u010denko, Dragan Savi\u0107 and \u0110or\u0111e Mali. Loba\u010dev's brother-in-law Valerian Apuhtin became the first professional [[letterer]] in Serbia. Another young artist at the time, [[\u017divorad Mitrovi\u0107]] would revisit this period in his 1982 film ''Savamala''.<ref>{{Citation|last=Mitrovic|first=Zivorad 'Zika'|title=Savamala|date=2000-01-01|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0173169/|accessdate=2016-07-20}}</ref>\n\nThe Golden Age of Serbian comics ended with the Nazi [[invasion of Yugoslavia]] in 1941. After [[World War II]] some authors were executed as [[Collaborationism|collaborators]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/k/kockar_vljko.htm|title=Veljko Kockar|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/s/sensin_ivan.htm|title=Ivan Sensin|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref> by [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia|the new communist regime]] or forced to [[Emigration|emigrate]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/k/kuznjecov_k.htm|title=Konstantin Kuznjecov|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/s/solovjev_sergej.htm|title=Sergej Solovjev|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-15}}</ref>\n\n=== 1945\u20131990 ===\nAfter World War II, the communist government considered comics a decadent product of the [[Western world#Cold War context|West]], therefore worthless and even harmful for children. In 1946 [[State-controlled media|state-owned]] daily newspaper ''[[Borba (newspaper)|Borba]]'' criticized comics as \"[[black market]] [[ersatz good]]s\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stripvesti.com/spec/knjiga/borba1.htm|title=index|website=www.stripvesti.com|access-date=2016-07-19}}</ref> For years to come, comics would be discouraged or outright banned. New magazines like ''Tri ugursuza'' (''Three Rowdies'', the Yugoslav title of ''[[Les Pieds Nickel\u00e9s]]'') and ''Vrabac'' (''The Sparrow'') were short-lived, although comic strips and cartoons survived in the humor magazines ''Je\u017e'' (''Hedgehog'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=392855|title=Oslobo\u0111enje i cenzura|access-date=2016-07-17}}</ref> and ''Mali Je\u017e'' (''Little Hedgehog''), where [[Milorad Dobri\u0107]] and Dejan Nasti\u0107 published in the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/dobric_milorad.htm|title=Milorad Dobric|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref>\n\nThe outlook changed after the [[Tito\u2013Stalin Split|Tito-Stalin Split]] in 1948. In 1951 Walt Disney\u2019s comics returned to Serbia\u2019s newspapers. In 1952 ''Politikin Zabavnik'' was revived, boasting a circulation of 450,000 in the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=369528|title=Formula udrobljenog sadr\u017eaja|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref> (The magazine is still published, having reached its 3000th issue in 2009.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politikin-zabavnik.co.rs/pz/tekstovi/na-rodjendan-pitinog-deteta|title=Broj 3000 {{!}} Politikin Zabavnik|website=politikin-zabavnik.co.rs|access-date=2016-07-17}}</ref> Loba\u010dev was welcomed back to the pages of ''Zabavnik'' in 1965. However, it would publish few local comics until [[Lazo Sredanovi\u0107]]\u2019s ''[[Dikan]]'' in 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=1129271|title=Buzdovan i meko srce|access-date=2016-07-17}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Dikan strip junak.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Dikan]]'' by Lazo Sredanovi\u0107 was commissioned by ''[[Politikin Zabavnik]]'' and modeled after ''[[Asterix]]''.]]\n\nNevertheless, back in the 1950s comic magazines like ''Robinzon'' (''[[Robinson Crusoe|Robinson]]'') and ''Veseli zabavnik'' were still censored, but even the [[Yugoslav People's Army]] started publishing some.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rastko.rs/strip/1/strip-u-srbiji-1955-1972/index_l.html|title=[Projekat Rastko] Zdravko Zupan: Strip u Srbiji 1955-1972.|website=www.rastko.rs|access-date=2016-07-17}}</ref> Zdravko Suli\u0107 began his career in such a publication, most of his works later published in the magazine [[Kekec (magazine)|''Kekec'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/s/sulic_zdravko.htm|title=Zdravko Sulic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref> It was launched by [[Borba (newspaper)|Borba]] in 1957, featuring French comics such as ''[[Lucky Luke]]'', [[The Smurfs|''Smurfs'']] and ''[[Chlorophylle]]'', but also domestic titles, including the works of \"the second generation\" of creators, like Aleksandar Hecl of ''Vinetu'' (''[[Winnetou]]'') fame.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/h/hecl_aleksandar.htm|title=Aleksandar Hecl|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-17}}</ref> The first [[CMYK color model|four-color]] ''Kekec'' publication reached the print run of 300,000 copies.<ref name=\":2\" /> ''Kekec'' lasted for 1532 issues and ended in 1990. \n\n\n\n1957 also saw teachers from the small town of [[Gornji Milanovac]] launch [[student newspaper]] ''[[De\u010dje novine]]'', which grew into a major publisher. Their most successful characters were [[Mirko and Slavko]], heroes of the [[eponym]]ous [[comic book]]. In the 1960s the adventures of the two [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisans]] peaked at 200,000 copies per issue. To date, it is the only Yugoslav comic adapted into a [[live action]] movie.<ref>Markovi\u0107, \u0110or\u0111e (2012). SFRJ za po\u010detnike. Delta Video.</ref> The title was serialized in the ''Nikad robom'' comic book series, which also printed works by Petar Radi\u010devi\u0107 (''Mystery Knight''), Radivoj Bogi\u010devi\u0107 (''Akant''), Bo\u017eidar Veselinovi\u0107 (''Dabi\u0161a'') and \u017divorad Atanackovi\u0107 (''Hajduk Veljko''), all inspired by the history of the [[South Slavs]]. The same publisher launched a number of other magazines, including ''Zenit'' and ''Biblioteka Lale'' (which first reprinted [[Marvel Comics|Marvel comics]] in Yugoslavia) and ''Eks almanah'' (which introduced [[DC Comics|DC]] [[superhero]]es, among others).\n\n[[File:Cover to YU strip issue 31, featuring Kobra, art by Branislav Kerac.jpg|left|thumb|''[[YU strip]]'' magazine cover, featuring ''[[Kobra (comic book)|Kobra]]'' by [[Branislav Kerac]], a comic which merged influences from [[Action film|action movies]] to [[Franco-Belgian comics|bandes dessin\u00e9es]].]]\nStarting as an ''Eks'' [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] in 1977, the ''[[YU strip]]'' magazine turned to be the seminal publication for Serbian authors. Teamed up with writer [[Svetozar Obradovi\u0107]], [[Branislav Kerac]] had already debuted with ''Lieutenant Tara'' in the ''Zlatni kliker'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bkerac.tripod.com/artist.htm|title=Comix Drawer|website=bkerac.tripod.com|access-date=2016-07-17}}</ref> The duo went on to create [[Kobra (comic book)|''Kobra'']], the most popular Yugoslav comic of the 1980s. Kerac\u2019s super-heroine [[Cat Claw]] reached even greater success abroad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/k/kerac_bane.htm|title=Bane Kerac|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-17}}</ref> A number of local creators ([[Zoran Janjetov]], [[R. M. Gu\u00e9ra|R.M. Guera]], [[Darko Perovi\u0107]], [[Zoran Tuci\u0107]], [[Vujadin Radovanovi\u0107]], [[\u017deljko Pahek]], [[Dejan Nenadov]], [[Vladimir Krsti\u0107 - Laci|Vladimir Krsti\u0107]] and many others) published their early stories in ''YU strip'' before they went on to work for foreign publishers. The magazine lasted for 85 issues and ended in 1987.\n\nBy the late 1970s, the scene rebounded after the blow it had suffered from the 1972 tax law<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=429075|title=Mirko, Slavko i Kekec|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref> which targeted not only the [[Yellow journalism|yellow press]] but also comics. From 1971 to 1981, 11,611 issues of comics and [[Pulp magazine|pulp novels]] were printed in Yugoslavia, a total of 717 million copies in the country of 22 million people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yugopapir.com/2015/01/fenomen-popularnosti-stripa-u.html|title=Yugopapir: Fenomen popularnosti stripa: U Jugoslaviji je od 1971 - 81. prodato 716 miliona primeraka|website=www.yugopapir.com|access-date=2016-07-22}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, the student press welcomed [[comics studies]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stripvesti.com/arhiva/sv-194.htm#djukanovic|title=SVesti|website=www.stripvesti.com|access-date=2016-07-18}}</ref> and [[alternative comics]] of \"the third generation\",<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kljaki\u0107|first=Ljubomir|date=1979|title=Quo vadis tre\u0107a generacijo?|url=|journal=\"Vidici\" br. 2|volume=|issue=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|via=}}</ref> inspired by ''[[M\u00e9tal hurlant]]''. The ''Pegaz'' magazine was another publication that nurtured comics theory; it was also where the award-winning  ''Svemironi'' strip by Lazar Stanojevi\u0107 premiered in 1975.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rastko.rs/strip/lstanojevic/lstanojevic-svemironi.html|title=[Projekat Rastko] Lazar Stanojevic: svemironi|website=www.rastko.rs|access-date=2016-07-21}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, comic groups like Belgrade Circle 2 and Bauhaus 7 appeared, comic album was introduced as a new format, and the first [[Animated cartoon|animated short]] based on a comic was filmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ljubac.rs/|title=LJUBOMIR MILOJEVI\u0106 LJUBAC - HOME|website=ljubac.rs|access-date=2016-07-30}}</ref> The mass media embraced comics insomuch that the [[Radio Television of Serbia|national television]] produced an educational series on the medium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rts.rs/page/tv/sr/story/255/rts-3/1526747/stripomanija-1-6.html|title=Stripomanija, 1-6|last=Serbia|first=RTS, Radio televizija Srbije, Radio Television of|access-date=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\nAnother new trend in the 1960s was the emergence of more comic magazines outside of Belgrade. Published by Forum in [[Novi Sad]], ''Panorama'' was eventually transformed into ''[[Stripoteka]]'', which reached issue 1000 in 2004<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://happynovisad.com/strip/stripoteka-broj-1000.270.html|title=STRIPOTEKA broj 1000!|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref> and still comes out today. [[Dnevnik (Serbia)|Dnevnik]] launched ''Zlatna serija'' and ''Lunov magnus strip'', featuring [[Italian comics|Italian comic books]] like [[Tex Willer|''Tex'']] and ''[[Zagor]]''. In the 1980s Kerac spearheaded teams of writers and artists working on [[Licensed production|licensed]] [[Tarzan (comics)|Tarzan]] and [[Il Grande Blek|Blek]] comics for these two publishers. The list included artists [[Branko Plav\u0161i\u0107]], [[Goran \u0110uki\u0107 Gorski (artist)|Goran \u0110uki\u0107]], [[Miodrag Ivanovi\u0107 Mikica|Miodrag Ivanovi\u0107]], [[Pavel Koza]], [[Marinko Lebovi\u0107]], [[Petar Meseld\u017eija]], Milan Mileti\u0107, [[Sibin Slavkovi\u0107]] and [[Dragan Stoki\u0107 Raja\u010dki]]. The [[Ninja (comic book)|Ninja]] and [[Mitar Milo\u0161evi\u0107|Lun kralj pono\u0107i]] comics were similarly manufactured, but were based on the Yugoslav pulp novels of the same names.\n\nUntil 1991 Serbian comics were part of Yugoslav comics. Distributed via newsstands, most comics were sold throughout Yugoslavia, written by and large in the common [[Shtokavian]] dialect and often printed in the Latin alphabet. \n\nPublications from other republics, especially Croatia, from Plavi Vjesnik to ''[[Alan Ford (comics)|Alan Ford]]'', had a great influence on creators and readers in Serbia. A [[Play (theatre)|play]] titled ''Alan Ford'' written by Mirjana Lazi\u0107 and directed by Kokan Mladenovi\u0107 was staged at Teatar T in Belgrade in 1994. [[Radio Belgrade]] produced a [[radio drama]] based on the play in 2002. \n\nAlso, authors worked for publishers outside Serbia, e.g. artists Du\u0161an Relji\u0107, Bojan \u0110uki\u0107, Ratomir Petrovi\u0107, [[Zdravko Zupan]], [[Nikola Maslovara]] and Zoran Kova\u010devi\u0107, as well as writer Lazar Odanovi\u0107 collaborated on the licensed [[Tom and Jerry]] comics for ''[[Vjesnik]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rastko.rs/strip/60godina/60gstripa_10.html|title=Slobodan Ivkov: 60 godina stripa u Srbiji|website=www.rastko.rs|access-date=2016-07-24}}</ref> Finally, artists exhibited at the joint Yugoslav Comics Festival in [[Vinkovci]] (Salon jugoslovenskog stripa).\n\nThe local comic book industry collapsed with the breakup of Yugoslavia.\n\n=== 1991 - present ===\n\n[[File:Treci_argument_cover.jpg|thumb|left|Graphic novel ''Tre\u0107i argument'' (''[[The Third Argument]]''), drawn by Zoran Tuci\u0107 and written by [[Zoran Stefanovi\u0107]], was based on the works of writer [[Milorad Pavi\u0107]].]]In the 1990s dozens of Serbian artists turned to foreign publishers. After ''Bernard Panasonik,'' Zoran Janjetov was chosen to work on ''Before the Incal'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/j/janjetov_z.htm|title=Zoran Janjetov|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> a prequel to [[The Incal|the original series]] by [[Jean Giraud|Moebius]] and [[Alejandro Jodorowsky|Jodorowsky]]. In 1998 Janjetov would go on to draw ''[[The Technopriests]]''. Darko Perovi\u0107 collaborated with writer [[Enrique S\u00e1nchez Abul\u00ed|Enrique Abuli]] before he started working on ''[[Magico Vento]]'' (written by [[Gianfranco Manfredi]]) for [[Sergio Bonelli Editore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/p/perovic_darko.htm|title=Darko Perovic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> In 1998 [[Aleksa Gaji\u0107]] graduated with ''[[Technotise]]'' ([[graphic novel]] written by Darko Grkini\u0107) from the [[University of Arts in Belgrade]] and went on to work for [[Soleil Productions]] as the illustrator on ''[[Scourge of the Gods]]''. In 2009 he would revisit those characters in his ''[[Technotise: Edit & I]]'' [[animated feature film]], first of its kind in Serbia.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/v/vesovic_vladimir.htm|title=Vladimir Vesovic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> R.M. Guerra worked in Europe for years<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/g/guera_rm.htm|title=R. M.  Gu\u00e9ra|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> before illustrating [[Jason Aaron]]\u2019s ''[[Scalped]]'' for DC Comics\u2019 [[Imprint (trade name)|imprint]] [[Vertigo (DC Comics)|Vertigo]] in 2007. \u017deljko Pahek and Zoran Tuci\u0107 published in [[Heavy Metal (magazine)|''Heavy Metal'']] and other magazines abroad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/p/pahek-zeljko.htm|title=Zeljko Pahek|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref>\n\nBack home, enthusiasts kept the scene alive. First [[Direct market|comic book stores]] were opened<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alanford.co.rs/o_nama/index.php|title=Alan Ford Knjizara|website=www.alanford.co.rs|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> and [[comic book convention]]s organized.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.danas.rs/kultura.11.html?news_id=322431|title=Balkanska smotra stripa|website=Dnevni list Danas|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> A co-founder of the [[International Comics Festival \"Salon stripa\"|International Comics Festival in Belgrade]] and teacher at the \u201c\u0110or\u0111e Loba\u010dev\u201c comics school, artist [[Vladimir Vesovi\u0107]] launched ''Tron'' in 1992<ref name=\":3\" /> and ''Stripmania'' in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ilijada.blogspot.com/search?q=mania|title=I L I J A D A: \u0420\u0435\u0437\u0443\u043b\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0438\u0432\u0430\u045a\u0430 \u0437\u0430 mania|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> The former also carried comics by local creators, such as ''Swindle'' by \u0110or\u0111e Milosavljevi\u0107 and Miroljub Milutinovi\u0107 Brada, which was adapted for television in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://superstartv.rs/serije/svindleri/|title=\u0160vindleri|date=2019-11-29|website=SUPERSTAR TV|language=sr-RS|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> The latter was printed by Luxor Comics, a publishing house owned by [[Milan Konjevi\u0107]], who also wrote and published ''[[Generation Tesla]]'' and ''Twilight Fighters'' in 1995, as well as ''Factor 4'' and ''Wild Magic'' in 2006, all titles drawn by Serbian artists. Before he started working for [[Dupuis]], artist [[Milan Jovanovi\u0107 (artist)|Milan Jovanovi\u0107]] teamed up with Croatian writer [[Darko Macan]] to produce [[La B\u00eate Noire (comics)|''La B\u00eate Noire'']] in 2002;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/j/jovanovic_milan.htm|title=Milan Jovanovic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> the five-part series was published by Zlatko Milenkovi\u0107, editor of the pioneering ''Strip vesti'' [[web portal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/v/vukic_bojan.htm|title=Bojan Vukic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> 2007 saw two more series appear; writer Marko Stojanovi\u0107 with a team of artists launched ''[[Vekovnici]]'' (''Endless''),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.systemcomics.com/web/content/view/83/99/|title=System Comics, Beograd - Vekovnici - autori|last=Stevanovic|first=Zoran|website=www.systemcomics.com|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> while Vladimir Tadi\u0107 created ''Zabava za celu porodicu'' (''Fun for the Whole Family'') with a different artistic team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stripovi.com/enciklopedija/strip/zzcp/zabava-za-celu-porodicu/|title=Zabava za celu porodicu - Enciklopedija - www.stripovi.com - Prozor u svijet stripa|website=www.stripovi.com|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> In a category of his own, award-winning illustrator<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.modestycomics.com/authors-a-m/djordje-milovic/|title=Modesty Comics - Djordje Milovic|website=www.modestycomics.com|access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref> [[\u0110or\u0111e Milovi\u0107]] continues to create his ''Stories about the Clay''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stripvesti.com/autori/milovic/index.htm|title=index|website=www.stripvesti.com|access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref> Forum's successor Marketprint revamped ''Stripoteka'' after an eight-year break in 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stripoteka-trigger.blogspot.com/p/1000-brojeva-stripoteke.html|title=Stripoteka: Stripoteka 1000|website=stripoteka-trigger.blogspot.com|access-date=2016-07-31}}</ref> and introduced ''[[Akira (manga)|Akira]]'' in 2002'',''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stripvesti.com/arhiva/sv-169.htm#marketprint|title=SVesti|website=www.stripvesti.com|access-date=2016-07-31}}</ref> officially the first [[manga]] title in Serbia. However, the circulations were low and the newsstand editions struggled to find their feet.\n\nMeanwhile, the [[Underground comix|underground comics]] experienced an unprecedented boom. Aleksandar Rakezi\u0107 alias [[Aleksandar Zograf]], author of ''Life Under Sanctions'' ([[Fantagraphics Books]], 1994), had laid a groundwork as a pioneer of comic [[fanzine]]s in the 1980s. A decade later, authors like Danilo Milo\u0161ev Wostok, Sa\u0161a Mihajlovi\u0107, Danijel Savovi\u0107, Radovan Popovi\u0107, Nikola Vitkovi\u0107, Lazar Bodro\u017ea and many others gathered around self-published editions and managed to create original and authentic works.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nevidljivi strip|last=Sekuli\u0107|first=Aleksandra|publisher=Narodna biblioteka Srbije|year=2011|isbn=978-86-7035-231-5|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://floatingworldcomics.com/archives/80|title=Oct. 2nd \u2013 ON THE MARGINS: NEW COMIX FROM CROATIA AND SERBIA {{!}} Floating World Comics|website=floatingworldcomics.com|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref> For the first time since the late 1980s, a comic was censored in Serbia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stripvesti.com/spec/pavle/pavle.htm|title=index|website=www.stripvesti.com|access-date=2016-07-30}}</ref> Some would eventually try their hand at mainstream, like Leonid Pilipovi\u0107<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bedetheque.com/biblio-auteur-11894-BD-Pilipovic-Leo.html|title=Pilipovic, L\u00e9o - Bibliographie d\u00e9taill\u00e9e|last=MAGNERON|first=Philippe|website=www.bedetheque.com|access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref> and Tihomir \u010celanovi\u0107,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/c/chelanovich_t.htm|title=Tiho Celanovic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref> or turn to illustration, like Neda Doki\u0107<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/dokic_n.htm|title=Neda Dokic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref> and Milan Pavlovi\u0107.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mrstocca.blogspot.com/|title=Mr. Stocca|access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref>\n\nIn the 21st century new publishers (such as Lavirint, System Comics, Komiko, Darkwood, Rosenkrantz and others) continue to nurture international as well as Serbian comics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stripvesti.com/izdavaci/index.html|title=Strip vesti|website=www.stripvesti.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> However, the print runs remain limited, so artists have been forced to seek work abroad, especially in France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/kultura/vesti/srbija-uvozi-stripove-domacih-autora/wqbptln|title=Srbija uvozi stripove doma\u0107ih autora|date=2015-11-28|language=sr-SP|access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref> The list includes Vladimir Aleksi\u0107,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bedetheque.com/auteur-18233-BD-Aleksic-Vladimir.html|title=Aleksic, Vladimir - Bibliographie, BD, photo, biographie|last=MAGNERON|first=Philippe|website=www.bedetheque.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> Tiberiu Beka,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/t/tiberiu.htm|title=Tibery|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> Mirko \u010colak,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/c/colak_mirko.htm|title=Mirko Colak|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> Bojan Kova\u010devi\u0107,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/k/kovacevic_bojan.htm|title=Bojan Kovacevic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> [[Dra\u017een Kova\u010devi\u0107]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/k/kovacevic_drazen.htm|title=Drazen Kovacevic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> Miroljub Milutinovi\u0107,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/b/brada.htm|title=Brada|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> Sini\u0161a Radovi\u0107,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/r/radovic_sinisa.htm|title=Sinisa Radovic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> Bojan Vuki\u0107<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lambiek.net/artists/v/vukic_bojan.htm|title=Bojan Vukic|website=lambiek.net|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> and others. Comics in Serbia had all but retreated to bookstores and galleries until publisher Veseli \u010detvrtak reintroduced Bonelli comics to the newsstands in 2008. As of 2018, the best-selling graphic novel in recent history has been ''Sat'' (''Watch''), a [[World War I|WW1]] story written by [[Dragan de Lazare|Dragan Lazarevi\u0107 De Lazare]] and drawn by [[Vujadin Radovanovi\u0107|Vujadin Radovanovi\u0107 Vuja]] with colors by [[Rade Tovladijac]]; it was distributed in 120,000 copies via daily ''[[Ve\u010dernje novosti]]'' to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the [[Armistice of 11 November 1918]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usus.org.rs/21-najava/647-120-000-%D0%BF%D0%BE%D0%BA%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B0-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%98%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B6%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%98%D0%B8-%D1%81%D1%80%D0%BF%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8-%D1%81%D1%82%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%BF-%D0%BA%D0%B0%D0%BE-%D0%B4%D0%B0%D1%80-%D0%B7%D0%B0-%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%B8%D1%88%D1%9A%D0%B8%D1%86%D1%83-%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%BC%D0%B8%D1%80%D1%98%D0%B0-%D1%83-%D0%B2%D0%B5%D0%BB%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%BC-%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%82%D1%83|title=Udru\u017eenje stripskih umetnika Srbije|website=www.usus.org.rs|language=sr-rs|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019 a [[Interactive fiction|text-based video-game]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/app/983290/Lightstep_Chronicles/|title=Lightstep Chronicles on Steam|website=store.steampowered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> loosely based on Milo\u0161 Slavkovi\u0107's  ''Lightstep Chronicles'' comic was developed by [[Eipix Entertainment]]; the book itself was funded on [[Kickstarter]] in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/imagineincredible/lightstep-chronicles-retro-futurist-space-opera-co|title=LIGHTSTEP CHRONICLES \u2013 Retro Futurist Space Opera Comic Book|website=Kickstarter|language=en|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> and published by [[Dark Horse Comics|Dark Horse]] a year later.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digital.darkhorse.com/books/22d7093506af4447954bdfc478b90a81/lightstep|title=Lightstep {{!}} Dark Horse Digital Comics|website=digital.darkhorse.com|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 [[Radio Television of Vojvodina]] aired ''Kvadrati i obla\u010di\u0107i'' (''Panels and word-balloons''), a [[Documentary film|documentary series]] featuring interviews with local authors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rtv.rs/sr_lat/vojvodina/novi-sad/dokumentarni-serijal-kvadrati-i-oblacici-od-petka-na-rtv1_970592.html|title=Dokumentarni serijal \"Kvadrati i obla\u010di\u0107i\" od petka na RTV1|last=Vojvodine|first=Javna medijska ustanova JMU Radio-televizija|website=JMU Radio-televizija Vojvodine|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== List of Serbian comics ==\n\n* [[La B\u00eate Noire (comics)|''La B\u00eate Noire'']]\n* ''[[Il Grande Blek#Yugoslavia|YU Blek]]''\n* ''[[Cat Claw]]''\n* ''[[Dikan]]''\n* ''[[Generation Tesla]]''\n* ''[[Kobra (comic book)|Kobra]]''\n* ''[[Master Death (comics)|Master Death]]''\n* ''[[Mirko and Slavko]]''\n* ''[[Ninja (comic book)|Ninja]]''\n* ''[[Prijatelji (comics)|Prijatelji]]''\n* ''[[Tarzan (comics)#Europe|Tarzan (Yugoslavian Version)]]''\n* ''[[Technotise]]''\n* ''[[The Third Argument]]''\n* ''[[The Thread of Art]]''\n* ''[[Zigomar (comics)|Zigomar]]''\n\n== List of Serbian comics people ==\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=18em|;Artists\n* [[Aleksa Gaji\u0107]]\n* [[Borivoje Grbi\u0107]]\n* [[Zoran Janjetov]]\n* [[Branislav Kerac]]\n* [[Vladimir Krsti\u0107 - Laci]]\n* [[Dra\u017een Kova\u010devi\u0107]]\n* [[Dragan de Lazare]]\n* [[\u0110or\u0111e Loba\u010dev]]\n* [[Nikola Maslovara]]\n* [[Petar Meseld\u017eija]]\n* [[R. M. Gu\u00e9ra|Rajko Milo\u0161evi\u0107 a.k.a. Gera and R.M. Gu\u00e9ra]]\n* [[Jovan Nikoli\u0107 (cartoonist)|Jovan Nikoli\u0107]]\n* [[Darko Perovi\u0107]]\n* [[Branko Plav\u0161i\u0107]]\n* [[Vujadin Radovanovi\u0107]]\n* [[Sibin Slavkovi\u0107]]\n* [[Gradimir Smudja]]\n* [[Rade Tovladijac]]\n* [[Zoran Tuci\u0107]]\n* [[Jugoslav Vlahovi\u0107]]\n* [[Dobrosav \u017divkovi\u0107]]\n* [[Aleksandar Zograf]]\n* [[Zdravko Zupan]]\n\n;Writers\n* [[Branko \u0106opi\u0107]]\n* [[Dobrica Eri\u0107]]\n* [[Boban Kne\u017eevi\u0107]]\n* [[Milan Konjevi\u0107]]\n* [[Svetozar Obradovi\u0107]]\n* [[Du\u0161ko Radovi\u0107]]\n* [[Zoran Stefanovi\u0107]]\n* [[Slobodan \u0160kerovi\u0107]]\n\n;Editors, critics, researchers\n* [[Mom\u010dilo Rajin]]\n* [[\u017divojin Tamburi\u0107]]\n* [[Bogdan Tirnani\u0107]]\n* [[Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107 (writer)|Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107]]\n}}\n\n== List of films based on Serbian comics ==\n\n* ''[[Mirko and Slavko#Film adaptation|Mirko and Slavko]]'' (1973)<ref>{{Citation|last=Jankovic|first=Branimir Tori|title=Mirko and Slavko|date=1973-11-21|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0181690/|accessdate=2016-07-12}}</ref>\n* ''[[Cat Claw#TV Movie|City Cat]]'' (1991), TV short based on [[Cat Claw]]\n* ''[[Technotise Edit & I]]'' (2008), animated, based on [[Technotise]]\n*''[[imdbtitle:10934170|The Swindlers]]'' (2020), TV show\n\n==List of comic festivals in Serbia==\n\n*Balkanska smotra mladih strip autora, [[Leskovac]]\n*Bijenale jugoslovenskog stripa, [[Zemun]]\n*Beogradski sajam knjiga, Beograd\n*Dani stripa, Gornji Milanovac\n*Dani stripa, [[Ni\u0161]]\n*Dani stripa u Poletu, Beograd\n*Ga\u0161in sabor, festival karikaturalnog stripa, Beograd\n*GRRR festival alternativnog stripa, [[Pan\u010devo]]\n*Kragujevac Comic Con, [[Kragujevac]]\n*Nifest, Ni\u0161\n*Novo doba, festival nesvrstanog stripa, Beograd\n*Novosadski strip vikend, Novi Sad\n*Pirot grad stripa, [[Pirot]]\n*Salon doma\u0107eg stripa, Kragujevac\n*Salon jugoslovenskog stripa, Pan\u010devo\n*Salon stripa, Beograd\n*Salon stripa, [[Zaje\u010dar]]\n*Somborski strip fest, [[Sombor]]\n*Strika fest, Festival stripa i karikature, [[Po\u017earevac]]\n*Strip kolonija, [[Ra\u0161ka]]\n*Stripolis, festival stripa, [[Zrenjanin]]\n*Striporama fest, Ni\u0161\n*Striposlavija, Beograd\n*\u0160aba\u010dki festival stripa, [[\u0160abac]]\n*Tras, Beograd\n*Valjevski strip festival, [[Valjevo]]\n*Vikend stripa, Valjevo\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[:Category:Croatian comics|Croatian comics]]\n*[[American comic book|American comics]]\n*[[Franco-Belgian comics]]\n*[[Spanish comics]]\n*[[Italian comics]]\n*[[Argentine comics]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [[\u017dika Bogdanovi\u0107|Bogdanovi\u0107, \u017dika]] et al. ''Umetnost i jezik stripa'', \u201eOrbis\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1994.\n* Bogdanovi\u0107, \u017dika. ''\u010cardak ni na nebu ni na zemlji: Ra\u0111anje i \u017eivot beogradskog stripa 1934-1941, ''\u201eAteneum\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia, 2006.\n* [[Borisav \u010celikovi\u0107|\u010celikovi\u0107, Borisav]], \u201e\u010cetiri decenije stripa De\u010djih novina i Stripografija edicije Nikad robom\u201c, ''Dani stripa \u201895''. \u201eDe\u010dje novine\u201c, Gornji Milanovac (Yugoslavia), 1995.\n* [[Slavko Dragin\u010di\u0107|Dragin\u010di\u0107, Slavko]] & [[Zdravko Zupan]]. ''Istorija jugoslovenskog stripa ''1'', ''\u201eForum\u201c, Novi Sad, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1986.\n* [[Zoran \u0110ukanovi\u0107|\u0110ukanovi\u0107, Zoran]]. ''Thomas Man ili Filip K. Dik, ''Vidici, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1988. (extended e-publication: www.stripovi.com, 2006)\n* [[Branko \u0110uki\u0107|\u0110uki\u0107, Branko]] et al. ''Zrenjaninski strip almanah'', Kulturni centar, Zrenjanin, Serbia, 2007.\n* [[Didier Ghez|Ghez, Didier]] & Zdravko Zupan''. ''\u201eEuropean Disneyana, part III \u2013 Yugoslavia\u201c'', Tomart\u2019s Disneyana'' 44, Dayton, Ohio, USA, 2001.\n* [[Maurice Horn|Horn, Maurice]] et al. ''The World Encyclopedia of Comics,'' [[Chelsea House Publishers]], Broomall, USA, 1976 & 1999.\n* [[Slobodan Ivkov|Ivkov, Slobodan]]. ''60 godina doma\u0107eg stripa u Srbiji 1935-1995, ''Galerija \u201eLikovni susret\u201c, Subotica, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1995.\n* [[Sre\u0107ko Jovanovi\u0107|Jovanovi\u0107, Sre\u0107ko]]. ''Veliki san, ''&nbsp;ed. by Vasa Pavkovi\u0107 and Zdravko Zupan, \u201eArhiv\u201c, Pan\u010devo, Serbia, 2007.\n* [[Johanna Marcad\u00e9|Marcad\u00e9, Johanna]]. ''Stripovi/\u0421\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0438, Bande dessin\u00e9e ind\u00e9pendante et contemporaine en Serbie et en Croatie'', Turbo Comix/Le Courrier des Balkans, Belgrade/Paris, 2009.\n* [[Branislav Miltojevi\u0107|Miltojevi\u0107 Branislav]] et al. ''Antologija ni\u0161kog stripa'', \u201eProsveta\u201c, Ni\u0161, Serbia, 2004.\n* [[Ranko Muniti\u0107|Muniti\u0107, Ranko]]. ''Deveta umetnost: strip, ''\u201eImage\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia, 2006.\n* [[Svetozar Obradovi\u0107|Obradovi\u0107, Svetozar]] et al. ''Novosadski strip'', \u201ePrometej\u201c, Novi Sad, Serbia, 2007.\n* [[Milenko Paji\u0107|Paji\u0107, Milenko]] i [[Vladimir Dunji\u0107]]. ''Studio za novi strip: Lu\u010dani 1975-1980'', \u201eAcademica\u201c, U\u017eice, Serbia, 2007.\n* [[Vasa Pavkovi\u0107|Pavkovi\u0107, Vasa]]. ''Na\u0161 slatki strip, ''\u201eNarodna knjiga\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Serbia & Montenegro), 2003.\n* [[Petar Radi\u010devi\u0107|Radi\u010devi\u0107, Petar]], ''Ilustrovana istorija stripa ''(''Eks-almanah \u2013 Specijal'', br. 169/I)'', ''\u201eDe\u010dje novine\u201c, Gornji Milanovac, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1979.\n* [[Zoran Stefanovi\u0107|Stefanovi\u0107, Zoran]]. Essays and studies in ''Dikan. Vol. 1'' ''(1969-1971)'', by [[Lazo Sredanovi\u0107]], [[Nikola Leki\u0107]] et al, \"Everest Media\", Belgrade 2013. {{ISBN|978-86-7756-027-0}} and ''Dikan. Vol. 2 (1972-1983)'', \u201eInformatika\u201c & \u201eEverest media\u201c, Beograd 2015. {{ISBN|978-86-84497-49-1}}\n* Stefanovi\u0107, Zoran. \"Siktaj bez zvuka: kriti\u010dka istorija serijala Kobra\", in: Kobra, Vol. 1, by Svetozar Obradovi\u0107 and [[Branislav Kerac]], \"Darkwood\", Belgrade, 2013, pp. 157\u2013189. {{ISBN|978-86-6163-139-9}}\n* Stojanovi\u0107, Marko et al. ''Leskova\u010dki strip 1950-2010'', own publication, Leskovac, Serbia, 2010.\n* [[\u017divojin Tamburi\u0107|Tamburi\u0107, \u017divojin]], Zdravko Zupan and Zoran Stefanovi\u0107, with foreword by [[Paul Gravett]]. ''[[The Comics We Loved|The Comics We Loved: Selection of 20th Century Comics and Creators from the Region of Former Yugoslavia'']], \"Omnibus\", Belgrade, Serbia, 2011. {{ISBN|978-86-87071-03-2}}\n* [[Bogdan Tirnani\u0107|Tirnani\u0107, Bogdan]]. ''Ogled o Paji Patku, ''\u201eXX vek\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1989.\n* [[Svetozar Tomi\u0107|Tomi\u0107, Svetozar]]. ''Strip, poreklo i zna\u010daj, ''\u201eForum\u201c, Novi Sad, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1985.\n* [[Anica Tucakov|Tucakov, Anica]]. ''Strip u Srbiji 1975-1995, ''Zadu\u017ebina \u201eAndrejevi\u0107\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 2000.\n* Various. ''Izme\u0111u igre i podviga: Ko je i kako stvarao De\u010dje novine'', ed. by Aleksandar Lazarevi\u0107, \u201eRavera Press\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1996.\n* Zupan, Zdravko, \u201eLes \u00e9ditions europ\u00e9ennes du journal de Mickey \u2013 Yougoslavie\u201c, ''Le collectionneur de Bandes Dessin\u00e9es'' 105, Paris, France, 2005.\n* Zupan, Zdravko, \u201eThe Golden Age of Serbian comics, Belgrade Comic Art 1935-1941\u201c'', International Journal of Comic Art, ''Drexel Hill, PA, USA, 2000.\n* Zupan, Zdravko. ''Vek stripa u Srbiji, ''Kulturni centar, Pan\u010devo, Serbia, 2007.\n* [[Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107 (writer)|\u017divkovi\u0107 Zoran]]. ''Enciklopedija nau\u010dne fantastike ''1-2, \u201eProsveta\u201c, Belgrade, Serbia (Yugoslavia), 1990.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150323215621/http://www.rastko.org.rs/strip/zzupan-golden_age.html The Golden Age of Serbian Comics] {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://www.paulgravett.com/articles/article/comics_culture_in_yugoslavias_ Comics Culture in Yugoslavia by Paul Gravett] {{in lang|en}}\n*[http://www.rastko.org.rs/strip/zstefanovic-petlic_c.html Konstantin Kuznjecov, ''Fairytale about Tsar Saltan/The Tale of the Golden Cockerel'', 1940] {{in lang|sr}}\n*[http://www.stripvesti.com/ Strip vesti (comics news)] {{in lang|sr}}\n*[http://www.kosmoplovci.net/studiostrip/indexx.html Kosmoplovci (Serbian underground comics)] {{in lang|sr}}\n*[http://www.usus.org.rs/ The Association of Serbian comics artists/Udru\u017eenje stripskih umetnika Srbije] {{in lang|sr}}\n\n{{Comics}}\n", "name_user": "Wyatt Tyrone Smith", "label": "safe", "comment": "fes